1 That sun which before warmed my breast with love, 2 had uncovered to me the beautiful truth, 3 proving and re-proving, the sweet appearance;
4 and I, to confess correctly and certainly 5 myself, as much as was fitting, 6 raised my head to utter more uprightly;
7 but a vision appeared which held me 8 so tightly to itself, to see itself, 9 that of my confession I did not remember.

10 As through transparent and clear glasses, 11 or through clear and tranquil waters, 12 not so deep that the bottoms are lost,
13 return to our eyes the postscripts 14 so weak, that a pearl on a white forehead 15 does not come less strongly to our pupils;
16 such I saw many faces ready to speak; 17 for which I ran within the contrary error 18 to that which ignited love between man and the fountain.

